content.description: A tricky start leads to steep bulges, and finishes with a fun roof move.   May be a bit sandy.
content.location: This is the sport route just to the right of Starship Trooper and the obvious dihedral.

content.description:
This is the warm-up of the area, with fun face climbing up good rock.  Cruxy at the bottom & top, with fun cruising in between. 

  Follow bolts up and left, then back right, then straight up to the anchor.
content.protection: Well bolted, with a bolted anchor.
content.location: Located right of Space Cowboy, just left of the obvious corner crack.

content.description: Arete to the left of Mission To Mars. This route is really, really fun.
Fun face climbing leads to a solution pocket crux.
content.location: Just north of the Satellite Wall, on the way to The Beach and Upper Beach areas. Scramble up an easy groove to the base of the climb.

content.description: Newer route to the left of the main area, cool slab climbing up to awkward move into pod/chimney and out roof.  Pretty sure Erik Wolfe put this up, was out with John Burcham and saw him cleaning something in this area.
content.location: Left of the main are crawl through the tunnel at "Do the Boscoe" and you'll see it.

content.description: Best 12d in Arizona.  Short vertical section gets you to a ledge for a rest.  Then blast off up steep rock on good holds.  Great moves all the way to the anchor.
content.location: Obvious line on the left side of the cave.

content.description: This route would feel harder if not for the napping ledge in the middle. Excellent crux above the ledge, followed by some long juggy pulls.
content.location: Lunar Lander is left of Mission to Mars and starts up a chossy slab which reportedly used to have a fixed line ascending it which is now gone. A new line - Gravitational Pull 12d - veers right after the 6th bolt and crux of Lunar Lander, and finishes at the Mission to Mars anchor.

content.description: A good, vertical sport route with a couple cruxes and a spicy feeling finish.
content.location: This route lies 200 yards right of the Planetarium proper. Follow the cliff base right from the Planetarium until you come almost to the end of the cliff. Look for bolts on a faint arete feature in the first 40 feet.

content.description: Easy slab climbing up to steep moves into poorer quality rock.  Decent route, not as good as other route in area though.
content.location: Left of Unknow?, left of the main area

content.description: Starts on Lunar Lander through bolt 6 then does a cool traverse right and pulls the crux through the obvious roof.  Pass anchor above the roof and finish on M2M anchor.  Lower anchor is helpful for cleaning.  A great addition to a great crag!

Cool route up the right side of the cave.  Start in a dihedral and stem up to the roof.  Pull the roof and take a rest.  Don't clip the bolt in the upper dihedral (the straight up version has not been sent).  Clip the bolt on the right, move right, then up and back left to the top of the dihedral.  Up to anchors.  The crux is after the rest and is a powerful boulder problem.
Scary crack to the left of Space Cowboys.

This is a nice route named after a great dog and his reaction to falling rocks.

 I have always found the start to be harder than the supposed crux. Even on the send I knew it was going to go once I to got to the rest below the crux without falling. However it seems most people feel differently, so check it out and see for yourself.

 Boulder up & right out of the cave on stout moves to a rest. Continue up to a good stance below the crux. Clip the bolt and gun it for the next one. Continue up easier but thoughtful moves on softer rock to the anchor.
content.location: Start just left of Fractal Universe (the thin crack just left of Space Cowboys) in a small cave.

content.description: To the right of Galactic Hitchhiker.
I can't remember if David said this was 11- or 11+.  Anyway, the crack to the right of Space Cowboy
content.location: Left of Mission to Mars, right of Space Cowboy.

content.description: This West facing Wall holds some of the best concentrated sport climbing in Sedona. Rock quality runs from poor to great.
